SIMPLE: plant
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Plant
<hw>Plant</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>plante</ets>,
L. <ets>planta</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A vegetable; an organized
living being, generally without feeling and voluntary motion, and
having, when complete, a root, stem, and leaves, though consisting
sometimes only of a single leafy expansion, or a series of cellules, or
even a single cellule.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<note><p>⟦hand⟧ Plants are divided by their structure and methods of
reproduction into two series, <xex>ph⟦ae⟧nogamous</xex> or
<xex>flowering plants</xex>, which have true flowers and seeds, and
<xex>cryptogamous</xex> or <xex>flowerless plants</xex>, which have no
flowers, and reproduce by minute one-celled spores. In both series are
minute and simple forms and others of great size and complexity.⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p> As to their mode of nutrition, plants may be considered as
<xex>self-supporting</xex> and <xex>dependent</xex>.
<xex>Self-supporting plants</xex> always contain chlorophyll, and
subsist on air and moisture and the matter dissolved in moisture, and as
a general rule they excrete oxygen, and use the carbonic acid to combine
with water and form the material for their tissues. <xex>Dependent
plants</xex> comprise all fungi and many flowering plants of a parasitic
or saprophytic nature. As a rule, they have no chlorophyll, and subsist
mainly or wholly on matter already organized, thus utilizing carbon
compounds already existing, and not excreting oxygen. But there are
plants which are partly dependent and partly self-supporting.⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p> The movements of climbing plants, of some insectivorous plants, of
leaves, stamens, or pistils in certain plants, and the ciliary motion of
zoospores, etc., may be considered a kind of voluntary
motion.⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p></note>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A bush, or young tree; a sapling; hence, a stick or
staff.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧A <xex>plant</xex> of stubborn oak.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The sole of the foot.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>
⟦ldquo⟧Knotty legs and <xex>plants</xex> of clay.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>B.
Jonson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Com.)</fld> <def>The whole machinery and apparatus
employed in carrying on a trade or mechanical business; also, sometimes
including real estate, and whatever represents investment of capital in
the means of carrying on a business, but not including material worked
upon or finished products; <as>as, the <ex>plant</ex> of a foundry, a
mill, or a railroad</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A plan; an artifice; a swindle; a trick.</def>
<mark>[Slang]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It was n't a bad <qex>plant</qex>, that of mine, on Fikey.</q>
<rj><qau>Dickens.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>An oyster which has
been bedded, in distinction from one of natural growth.</def>
<sd>(b)</sd> <def>A young oyster suitable for transplanting.</def>
<mark>[Local, U.S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- a person who joins a group, to spy on them on behalf of another
person or group -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Plant bug</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>any one of
numerous hemipterous insects which injure the foliage of plants, as
<spn>Lygus lineolaris</spn>, which damages wheat and trees.</cd> --
<col><b>Plant cutter</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a South American
passerine bird of the genus <gen>Phytotoma</gen>, family
<fam>Phytotomid⟦ae⟧</fam>. It has a serrated bill with which it cuts off
the young shoots and buds of plants, often doing much injury.</cd> --
<col><b>Plant louse</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>any small
hemipterous insect which infests plants, especially those of the
families <fam>Aphid⟦ae⟧</fam> and <fam>Psyllid⟦ae⟧</fam>; an
aphid.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Plant</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Plant
<hw>Plant</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Planted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Planting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>plantian</ets>, L.
<ets>plantare</ets>. See <er>Plant</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To put in the ground and cover, as seed for growth;
<as>as, to <ex>plant</ex> maize</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To set in the ground for growth, as a young tree, or
a vegetable with roots.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou shalt not <qex>plant</qex> thee a grove of any trees.</q>
<rj><qau>Deut. xvi. 21.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To furnish, or fit out, with plants; <as>as, to
<ex>plant</ex> a garden, an orchard, or a forest</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To engender; to generate; to set the germ
of.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It engenders choler, <qex>planteth</qex> anger.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To furnish with a fixed and organized population; to
settle; to establish; <as>as, to <ex>plant</ex> a colony</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Planting</qex> of countries like planting of woods.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To introduce and establish the principles or seeds
of; <as>as, to <ex>plant</ex> Christianity among the
heathen</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>To set firmly; to fix; to set and direct, or point;
<as>as, to <ex>plant</ex> cannon against a fort; to <ex>plant</ex> a
standard in any place; to <ex>plant</ex> one's feet on solid ground; to
<ex>plant</ex> one's fist in another's face.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>To set up; to install; to instate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We will <qex>plant</qex> some other in the throne.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Plant</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Plant
<hw>Plant</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To perform the act of
planting.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I have <qex>planted</qex>; Apollos watered.</q> <rj><qau>1 Cor.
iii. 6.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Plantable</ent>⟦br⟧
